Problem 1: Guided Visualization

In this part of the assignment, you will generate five graphs from this dataset meeting the provided requirements. You should be able to build these visualizations without using the dplyr library.

Part A

Generate a scatterplot showing the miles per gallon that the vehicle experiences during city driving on the x-axis and the vehicles CO2 emissions on the y-axis.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data=vehicles) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=citympg,
                         y=co2emissions))

Part B

Create a second scatterplot showing the same information as the plot from Part A but use color to distinguish vehicles by drive type.

ggplot(data=vehicles) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=citympg,
                         y=co2emissions,
                         color=drive))

Part C

Create a stacked bar chart that shows the number of vehicles tested each year broken out by vehicle class.

ggplot(data=vehicles) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=year,
                       fill=class))

Problem 2 - Working with dplyr

In this part of the assignment, you will expand your work to use the dplyr grammar of data manipulation.

For each part below, use a single R statement to perform the task. You may do this by joining together dplyr verbs and the ggplot commands with %>% and +.

Part A

Print a table showing the minimum, maximum, mean, and median city MPG for vehicles tested, broken out by vehicle class. All values should be displayed as integers. Use the as.integer() and round() functions, as necessary.

library(dplyr)
vehicles%>%
  group_by(class)%>%
  summarise(min=min(citympg),
           med=as.integer(median(citympg)),
           mean=as.integer(round(mean(citympg))),
           max=max(citympg))

Part B

Display a line graph showing the change in average city vs.highway MPG over time. Do not round the data to integers this time. Show the city MPG as a red line and the highway MPG as a blue line.

You do not need to add a legend to this diagram. The structure of the data would make this somewhat complicated. Well discuss that more when we get to data wrangling.

vehicles%>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  summarise(avg_citympg=mean(citympg),avg_highwaympg=mean(highwaympg))%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=avg_citympg),
                        color='red')+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=avg_highwaympg),
                        color='blue')+
  theme_classic()+
  ylab('average_mpg')

Part C

Modify the graph above to also show the overall MPG, computed as the average of city and highway MPG. Plot this as a green line.

vehicles%>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  summarise(avg_citympg=mean(citympg),
            avg_highwaympg=mean(highwaympg),
            overall_mpg=avg_citympg+avg_highwaympg)%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=avg_citympg),
                        color='red')+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=avg_highwaympg),
                        color='blue')+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=overall_mpg),
                        color='green')+
  theme_classic()+
  ggtitle('Overall Mile per Gallon by Year')

  ylab('average_mpg')

Part D

Modify the graph above to show separate graphs for each drive type.

vehicles%>%
  group_by(year,drive)%>%
  summarise(avg_citympg=mean(citympg),
            avg_highwaympg=mean(highwaympg),
            overall_mpg=avg_citympg+avg_highwaympg)%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=avg_citympg),
                        color='red')+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=avg_highwaympg),
                        color='blue')+
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=year,
                        y=overall_mpg),
                        color='green')+
  facet_wrap(~drive)+
  theme_classic()+
  ggtitle('Overall Mile per Gallon by Year')+
  ylab('Average Mpg')

#The visualizaiton I designed below shows the Admission rate of universities with bechalor and graduate as their highest degree in the state of Illinois. Also,this map allows us to compare the number of two types of univeristies.

library(tidyverse)
library(ggmap)
library(maps)
library(mapproj)

college <- read_csv("https://s3.amazonaws.com/itao-datasets/college.csv")
college <- college %>%
  mutate(state=as.factor(state), region=as.factor(region),
         highest_degree=as.factor(highest_degree),control=
         as.factor(control),gender=as.factor(gender),loan_default_rate
         =as.numeric(loan_default_rate))

IL_colleges = college %>%
  filter(state=='IL')
IL_mapdata <- map_data(map="county", region="Illinois")

ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data=IL_mapdata,aes(x=long,
                                   y=lat,
                                   group=group),
                                   color='black',
                                   fill='lightyellow1')+
  coord_map()+
  geom_point(data=IL_colleges,aes(x=lon,
                                  y=lat,
                                  color=highest_degree,
                                  size=admission_rate,
                                  alpha=0.89))+
  theme(panel.grid=element_blank(),
        panel.background=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks=element_blank(),
        axis.text=element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_blank())+
  ggtitle("Illinois Colleges and Universities",
          subtitle='Admission rate Distribution')+
  scale_alpha_continuous(guide=FALSE)+
  scale_color_discrete(name='Highest_degree')+
  scale_size_continuous(name='Admission Rate',range=c(1,7))

#I using the graphs below to show the relationship between loan default rate and the sat score. We could find that high sat score is associate with low loan defualt rate in each of the four regions. Also, I used gradient color to illustrate the number of schools in the graph.

college%>%
  mutate(high_score_percentage=sat_avg/n())%>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=high_score_percentage,
                     y=loan_default_rate))+
  geom_bin2d(bins=30)+
  facet_wrap(~region)+
  scale_fill_gradient(low="lightblue1",high="darkblue",trans="log10")+
  theme_light()+
  theme(axis.ticks=element_blank(),
        panel.grid=element_blank(),
        panel.background=element_blank())+
  ylab("Loan Default Rate")+
  xlab("Percantage of SAT Score")+
  ggtitle("Loan Default Rate Vaires with SAT Score", 
          subtitle='Source:U.S.Department of Education')
